	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Drakon</b> [ Sat Jun 25, 2011 6:52 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I actually didn't design the audio circuit.  Upgrading the av famicom is really popular in japan so this guy makes these custom designed pcbs just for it and sells them here:
<br />
<br /><a href="http://homepage3.nifty.com/F-LABO/ProductsList.html" class="postlink">http://homepage3.nifty.com/F-LABO/ProductsList.html</a>
<br />
<br />I've been using a proxy company to order these kits.  The instructions are all in japanese.  The pcb has everything clearly marked where to install all the parts.  The instruction paper tells you which marked spot takes which part if it's not already marked.  Here's pics of the pcb with no parts installed
<br />
<br /><img src="http://i240.photobucket.com/albums/ff253/TheDrakon/s-video%20kit/kittop.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br /><img src="http://i240.photobucket.com/albums/ff253/TheDrakon/s-video%20kit/kitbottom.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br />Here's the instructions:
<br />
<br /><img src="http://i240.photobucket.com/albums/ff253/TheDrakon/s-video%20kit/instructionsfront.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br /><img src="http://i240.photobucket.com/albums/ff253/TheDrakon/s-video%20kit/instructionsback.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br />The only part of the instructions that really need translating is where they tell you which colour rings corrospond to which resistor strength.  My girlfriend can read chinese so she made me a handy little chart:
<br />
<br /><img src="http://i240.photobucket.com/albums/ff253/TheDrakon/s-video%20kit/resistortranslation.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br />The video circuit is fairly simple.  Sync goes into a lm1881 and from the lm1881 output it goes into a cxa1645m.  I also tap the sync coming out of the lm1881 and wire that into the sync pin on the multi av port.  RGB go through 10uf caps and then straight into the cxa1645.  The cxa1645 amps the brightness and converts the video to very clean rgb, s-video, and composite.
<br />
<br />The audio circuit is indeed a couple of op amps and a virtual ground.  I wrote "very advanced" because I was posting this work on forums where people aren't very knowledgable and I just copy and pasted what I posted there.
<br />
<br />The clarity of the audio is caused by the audio circuit on this upgrade pcb.  The audio comparison video I made takes recordings from the same av famicom system before and after I modify the audio circuit.  I havn't analyzed it too thoroughly but I'm sure you guys can figure out what about it makes the audio so nice.
<br />
<br />The first kit I ordered for myself I chose not to get the audio circuit parts.  I didn't take interest in the audio mod at first but a lot of clients kept asking me about it and showed a lot of interest.  That's why I did the audio mod.
<br />
<br />The plus side of this kit is that all the pins of the rgb chip that don't connect to the system are seperated by the kit pcb traces.  Therefore if you want to use a composite ppu all you need to do is pull the kit out of the socket and stick a composite ppu into the socket.  The audio mod requires you to cut traces on the pcb so it's a bit more destructive.  Since I wire the audio connections into a header it would be fairly easy to wire the other end of the cut traces into a connection that would fit the header and restore the original circuit.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


